    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect Ethernet address printing in O-RAN fronthaul configuration\n\n### Summary\nThe `print_ether_addr` function in `radio/fhi_72/oran-config.c` was being called with incorrect address counts, causing it to access memory beyond what was allocated. This led to undefined behavior and incorrect output when printing Ethernet addresses.\n\nThe issue occurred because the function was using `fh_init->xran_ports * fh_init->io_cfg.num_vfs` as the count, which didn't match the actual number of Ethernet addresses allocated during initialization.\n\n### Changes\n- `radio/fhi_72/oran-config.c`: \n  - Added bounds checking in `print_ether_addr` to prevent accessing invalid memory\n  - Added `print_ether_addr_safe` function with upper limit checking\n  - Fixed count calculation for M-plane case to use correct formula based on `one_vf_cu_plane` flag\n  - Restructured printing logic to use appropriate count calculation per code path\n  - Removed inconsistent string printing of `p_o_du_addr`\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure O-RAN fronthaul with specific VF and port combinations\n2. Run the OAI software and trigger configuration printing\n3. Observe incorrect or garbled Ethernet address output, or potential segfaults\n\nThe symptoms included:\n- Incorrect number of Ethernet addresses printed\n- Garbled or invalid MAC addresses in output\n- Potential segmentation faults when accessing invalid memory\n"
}